@ijuma - thank you for the article, it was fascinating, and it may indeed be that our profiling runs were affected.

to gauge the effect of this change i used the following "micro-benchmark" (quoted because i didnt bother with a full JMH one):

``` java
@Test
def perfTest(): Unit = {
   val batchSize = 1
   var nanosTotal: Long = 0
   var runsTotal: Int = 0
   (1 to 1000000).foreach(i => {
     val messages = (1 to batchSize).map(m => {
       new Message((s"message num $m" + System.currentTimeMillis()).getBytes)
     })
     val messageSet = new ByteBufferMessageSet(GZIPCompressionCodec, messages: _*)
     var count = 0
     val start = System.nanoTime()
     messageSet.foreach((offset: MessageAndOffset) => {
       count += 1
     })
     val elapsed = System.nanoTime() - start
     assertEquals(batchSize, count)
     if (i > 100000) { //warm up iterations
       nanosTotal += elapsed
       runsTotal += 1
     }
   })
   val avg = nanosTotal / (runsTotal * 1000000.0)
   println(s"$avg ms on avg")
}
```

comparing the avg per-betch iteration time between vanilla Kafka and my patch shows it highly depends on the batch parameters.

The most extreme case is small batches and fast compression - batch size 1 + snappy show a ~x4 time improvement. this would be typical of environments where kafka would be used for real time messaging (tiny batches, fast compression).

On the other extreme (batch size 10000 + gzip) there's no noticeable difference.

Also no difference in case no compression was used.

@hachikuji @junrao @guozhangwang Sorry for the late reply. I am currently traveling and the network is a little flaky. 

@guozhangwang can you elaborate a little on the "not thread safe" purgatory? I am not sure what does that exactly mean. In the `DelayedOperationPurgatory`, we have locking on two things: 1) the lock on `operations` list and 2) the lock on each single operation.  

The first lock seems necessary to ensure the purgatory works correctly. The second lock is more of do a favor for the purgatory users.

Unfortunately, the current deadlock is caused by the first locking instead of the second one. i.e. Thread 1 holds the group lock and try to put a DelayedProduce into the purgatory `operations` list. Meanwhile thread 2 holds the purgatory `operations` list lock and try to lock the group when executing the delayed heartbeat.

So if the "not thread safe" purgatory means we do not perform the lock on each single operation, that seems not really help? Am I misunderstanding something?
